  <thing id="cNNWAccCrm" name="Accelerated Cruomancy" description="A sanguine aspirant&apos;s cruomancer level increases by 2 for every level of sanguine aspirant that she takes. Additionally, she gains a blood point pool with a maximum number of blood points equal to 3 + three times her sanguine aspirant level, as indicated on Table 3-1: The Sanguine Aspirant." compset="ClSpecial" summary="Maximum number of blood points equal to 3 + three times level">
    <tag group="Helper" tag="SpecUp"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="UseOwnLev"/>
    <eval phase="PostLevel" priority="10000"><![CDATA[
      ~ If we're not shown, just get out now
      doneif (tagis[Helper.ShowSpec] <> 1)
      ~ If we've been Disabled, get out now
      doneif (tagis[Helper.SpcDisable] <> 0)

      ~ We gain a double our level from this class special
      #value[xNNWCruLvl] += field[xTotalLev].value]]></eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNNWSAFrVu" name="Fire Vulnerability" description="The Sanguine Aspirant is exceptionally vulnerable to flames. She suffers half again as much damage (+50%) from any source that deals fire damage. Further, she also suffers a -4 penalty on saving throws made against spells or effects with the fire descriptor, and on saving throws made to avoid catching on fire or to stop being on fire once she already is. Finally, the very presence of fire can cause fear in the Sanguine Aspirant, and any Sanguine Aspirant within 30 feet of a flame larger than a candle must succeed on a Will save (DC 20) or be shaken for as long as she remains within range of the flame, and for 1d4 rounds thereafter. \n\nSanguine Aspirants that fail their saving throw by more than 10 (a result of 9 0r less) become frightened, instead. This is a mind-affecting fear effect, but the normal +4 bonus revenants gain on saving throws against mind-affecting effects does not apply." compset="CustomSpec" summary="Exceptionally vulnerable to flames. Will save (DC 20)" uniqueness="unique">
    <usesource source="srcLibVamp"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpNN4"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNNWSAGarl" name="Garlic" description="The Sanguine Aspirant recoils before garlic, and must stay at least five feet away from it, as long as it is strongly presented. She cannot touch or make melee attacks against a creature presenting garlic in this way. Any creature holding the revenant at bay in this manner must spend a standard action to do so. After one round, the Sanguine Aspirant can overcome her repulsion with a Will save (DC 25), and can act normally as long as she continues to make a DC 25 Will save each round.\n\nAdditionally, the Sanguine Aspirant cannot eat normal food. While no Sanguine Aspirant needs food to survive, Sanguine Aspirant without this weakness can consume food in order to pass as living creatures. Sanguine Aspirant with this weakness must succeed on a Will save (DC 15) in order to consume food, and doing so causes the Sanguine Aspirant to suffer from light necrosis for 24 hours, after which she takes 2d4 points of damage as the food is eventually expelled from her body." compset="CustomSpec" summary="Recoils before garlic. Will save (DC 25)" uniqueness="unique">
    <usesource source="srcLibVamp"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpNN4"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNNWSAGrvD" name="Grave Dirt" description="The Sanguine Aspirant must spend at least 8 hours per day resting in a coffin or similar container that contains at least 2 lbs. of soil from the graveyard in which the Sanguine Aspirant was buried. If the Sanguine Aspirant was never buried, then he becomes attuned to a specific graveyard upon becoming a Sanguine Aspirant (typically the one closest to him when he becomes a Sanguine Aspirant, but sometimes it is a graveyard of special significance, instead), and must rest in soil from this graveyard, instead. In either case, a Sanguine Aspirant that fails to rest in this way for a period 24 hours is affected by light necrosis. One that fails to rest in this way for a period of 3 days is affected by severe necrosis, instead. For each additional day that the Sanguine Aspirant does not rest in this way, she suffers 1d6 points of damage. This damage is not subject to damage reduction and cannot be prevented, nor can it be healed by any means until the Sanguine Aspirant spends at least 8 hours resting in a coffin or similar container containing at least 2 lbs. of soil from the appropriate graveyard, after which the damage can be healed normally. \n\nAdditionally, the Sanguine Aspirant does not cast a shadow. Anyone that observes the Sanguine Aspirant in a place where he should cast a notable shadow (places of normal light or brighter) can notice that he has no shadow with a successful DC 15 Perception check, which may alert him to the Sanguine Aspirant&apos;s true nature." compset="CustomSpec" summary="Spend at least 8 hours per day resting in a coffin." uniqueness="unique">
    <usesource source="srcLibVamp"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpNN4"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNNWSAGSVn" name="Great Sunlight Vulnerability" description="The Sanguine Aspirant is even more vulnerable to sunlight than most Sanguine Aspirant. As long as the Sanguine Aspirant is exposed to sunlight, she suffers from severe necrosis. Additionally, for every minute that she spends in an area of sunlight, she suffers 1 point of damage. \n\nThis damage cannot be prevented by any means, and cannot be healed until the Sanguine Aspirant has gone for at least 3 days without being exposed to sunlight of any kind. Further, damage inflicted in this way leaves horrible burns on the Sanguine Aspirant&apos;s skin, and extended exposure to sunlight may cause his body to visibly smoke and char, potentially alerting those who encounter him as to his true nature. Finally, whenever a Sanguine Aspirant that is currently exposed to sunlight spends blood points to activate an ability gained from a feat, class feature, or other source, he must spend 1 more blood points than he would otherwise have to in order to activate that ability (this stacks with the normal sunlight vulnerability weakness, for a total of 2 additional blood points)." compset="CustomSpec" summary="Even more vulnerable to sunlight" uniqueness="unique">
    <usesource source="srcLibVamp"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpNN4"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNNWSAHySy" name="Holy Symbols" description="The sanguine aspirant recoils before holy symbols, and must stay at least five feet away from them, as long as they are strongly presented. She cannot touch or make melee attacks against a creature presenting a holy symbol in this way. Any creature holding the sanguine aspirant at bay in this manner must spend a standard action to do so. After one round, the sanguine aspirant can overcome her repulsion with a DC 25 Will save, and can act normally as long as she continues to make a DC 25 Will save each round.\n\nAdditionally, the sanguine aspirant has difficulty entering churches, temples, and other places of worship. The sanguine aspirant must succeed on a Will save (DC 15) to enter such a location, and suffers from light necrosis for as long as she remains within. A failure on this Will save indicates that the sanguine aspirant cannot enter the holy place for 24 hours, and a failure by 5 or more indicates that she cannot enter for a full week. The exception to this is holy places devoted to a deity of undeath, which the revenant can enter without difficulty.\n\n{b}Defining Holy Symbols and Places of Worship{/b}\n\nThe &quot;holy symbols&quot; weakness of the revenant template causes the revenant to recoil from strongly-presented holy symbols, and makes it difficult for him to enter &quot;places of worship.&quot; While the definition of a holy symbol is typically fairly straightforward, and final determination will always lie with the GM, we present the following guidelines to help determine what this ability does and does not apply to:\n\nHoly symbols used for this ability can take other forms besides simply being a holy symbol. A specific deity&apos;s prayer book or holy book could suffice, as could a major image made to appear as the holy symbol. That said, just because a deity of war has a sword for his holy symbol does not necessarily mean that any old sword will work. The item must have been made with the intention of being used in that way. At the GM&apos;s discretion, a successful DC 20 Knowledge (religion) check could be used to cite scripture to keep the revenant at bay, instead of presenting a holy symbol.\n\nIn order to be a &quot;place of worship,&quot; a room or building must be used regularly and primarily as a place where religious services are performed. Long abandoned temples do not count, nor do all forests count as &quot;places of worship&quot; for a forest deity, etc." compset="CustomSpec" summary="Recoils before holy symbols. Will save (DC 25)" uniqueness="unique">
    <usesource source="srcLibVamp"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpNN4"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNNWSAMirr" name="Mirrors" description="The sanguine aspirant recoils before mirrors, and must stay at least five feet away from them, as long as they are strongly presented. She cannot touch or make melee attacks against a creature presenting a mirror in this way. Any creature holding the sanguine aspirant at bay in this manner must spend a standard action to do so. After one round, the sanguine aspirant can overcome her repulsion with a DC 25 Will save, and can act normally as long as she continues to make a DC 25 Will save each round.\n\nAdditionally, the sanguine aspirant&apos;s image is not reflected by mirrors or similar surfaces. Anyone that observes the sanguine aspirant in a place where he should be reflected by a mirror can notice that he has no reflection with a successful DC 15 Perception check, which may alert him to the sanguine aspirant&apos;s true nature." compset="CustomSpec" summary="Recoils before mirrors. Will save (DC 25)" uniqueness="unique">
    <usesource source="srcLibVamp"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpNN4"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNN1Bloodl" name="Bloodlust" description="Beginning at 1st level, a revenant bloodletter&apos;s powerful bloodlust grants him extra strength and vigor whenever he is exposed to the scent of fresh blood. Whenever the revenant bloodletter is within 30 feet of a living creature that could potentially be drained for blood points, and that has suffered hit point damage in the last hour, she gains a +2 enhancement bonus to her Strength score. This bonus lasts for as long as she remains within 30 feet of the creature, and for one round there after.\n\nAnything that would block the scent of blood (including other overpowering odors, an object or magic effect that blocks scent, etc.) prevents the revenant bloodletter from benefitting from this ability.\n\nAt 5th level, and every four levels thereafter, the enhancement bonus granted by this ability increases by an additional +2, to a maximum enhancement bonus of +10 at 17th level." compset="ClSpecial" summary="+2 enhancement bonus to her Strength score">
    <fieldval field="actName" value="Within 30ft of blood"/>
    <tag group="User" tag="Activation"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    <eval phase="PostLevel" priority="10000"><![CDATA[var bonus as number
bonus = field[xIndex].value * 2
~Set the list name
field[listname].text = field[thingname].text & " " & signed(bonus)

~ If we're not shown, just get out now
doneif (tagis[Helper.ShowSpec] <> 1)
~ if we've been disabled, get out now
doneif (tagis[Helper.SpcDisable] <> 0)

field[abValue].value += field[xCount].value * 2
field[livename].text = field[thingname].text & " " & signed(field[abValue].value)

~ only perform the rest on the first copy
doneif (tagis[Helper.FirstCopy] <> 1)
~ If not active get out now!
doneif (field[abilActive].value <> 1)

#applybonus[BonEnhance,hero.child[aSTR],field[abValue].value]]]></eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNNWSARnWt" name="Running Water" description="The sanguine aspirant is heavily damaged by immersion in running water, and has difficulty crossing over running water. Each round that the sanguine aspirant is in a body of running water, she must succeed on a Fortitude save (DC 15) or suffer an amount of damage equal to 1/3 her maximum hit points (rounded up). Even if the saving throw is a success, she still suffers 3d6 points of damage (or 1/3 her maximum hit points, whichever is less). This damage is not subject to damage reduction.\n\nAdditionally, the sanguine aspirant has difficulty crossing bodies of running water even if she does not need to immerse herself to do so. Any time that the sanguine aspirant attempts to cross a body of running water without immersing herself in it (such as by flying over it, walking across a bridge over it, rowing across it on a rowboat, etc.), she must succeed on a Will save (DC 15) or be unable to bring herself to do so. In the event of a failure, the sanguine aspirant can attempt to cross again in one hour. Nothing physically bars the sanguine aspirant from crossing the water in this fashion, and if the sanguine aspirant&apos;s movement across the running water is outside her control (for example, she is in a stagecoach that is being driven by another character, which crosses a bridge over running water), she may cross the water even if she fails her saving throw. Additionally, running water that is buried (such as sewers, underground rivers, etc.), do not prevent the sanguine aspirant from travelling at ground level." compset="CustomSpec" summary="Heavily damaged by immersion in running water. Fort save (DC 15)" uniqueness="unique">
    <usesource source="srcLibVamp"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpNN4"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNNWSASrVn" name="Silver Vulnerability" description="The sanguine aspirant is exceptionally vulnerable to silver. Any damage reduction that she gains, regardless of the source, can be overcome by silver weapons. Additionally, the sanguine aspirant suffers half again as much damage (1.5 times) from weapons made silver or other materials that count as silver for the purposes of bypassing damage reduction (this includes additional damage from a high Strength score, and feats and abilities like Power Attack or Weapon Specialization, but not additional damage dice, like sneak attack or the flaming weapon special ability).\n\nIn addition to the ill effects of being hit with a silver weapon, the mere touch of silver is physically painful to the sanguine aspirant, and she is sickened for as long as she touches or wears an object made of silver (including if it does not touch her skin directly, such as by handling it with gloves or similar), and suffers 1 point of damage each round that she maintains contact with an object made of silver." compset="CustomSpec" summary="Exceptionally vulnerable to silver." uniqueness="unique">
    <usesource source="srcLibVamp"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpNN4"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNNWSAStak" name="Stakes" description="The sanguine aspirant is particularly vulnerable to being staked through the heart with a wooden stake. Any character can drive a wooden stake through the heart of a helpless sanguine aspirant with this weakness as a full-round action. Alternatively, a character holding a wooden stake can attempt to drive it through the sanguine aspirant&apos;s heart while the sanguine aspirant is still able to defend himself. Doing so is a standard action that provokes attacks of opportunity unless the attacker is specifically proficient with wooden stakes as weapons, and requires a melee attack (characters not specifically proficient with wooden stakes suffer a -4 penalty on this attack roll, due to being non-proficient). If the attack hits, the sanguine aspirant must succeed on a Fortitude save (DC 25), or else the stake is driven through his heart.\n\nRegardless of the method by which the sanguine aspirant has a stake driven through his heart, the effects are the same: the sanguine aspirant suffers 4d8 points of piercing damage, to which damage reduction does not apply, and he is paralyzed for as long as the stake remains in place." compset="CustomSpec" summary="Vulnerable to being staked with a wooden stake. Fort save (DC 25)" uniqueness="unique">
    <usesource source="srcLibVamp"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpNN4"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNNWSAUmAp" name="Unmistakable Appearance" description="The sanguine aspirant&apos;s skin tone, sharp fangs, and glowing eyes betray her as an inhuman creature. Anyone that gets a clear look at the sanguine aspirant can see that she is not alive, and, with a successful DC 10 Knowledge (religion) check, can even identify her as a vampire of some sort. In general, characters that recognize the sanguine aspirant as an undead creature generally have their starting attitude towards the sanguine aspirant reduced by two steps (helpful becomes indifferent, friendly becomes unfriendly, indifferent becomes hostile, and so on). Further, characters that recognize that the sanguine aspirant is an undead creature generally cannot have an attitude towards the sanguine aspirant that is higher than friendly, no matter how skilled the sanguine aspirant is with Diplomacy (this does not prevent the target&apos;s attitude from being adjusted magically, such as with charm person).\n\nDifferent characters have different attitudes towards undead, however, and some characters may automatically be hostile and attempt to slay undead on sight, and some very rare individuals may actually have their starting attitude increased when they learn that the sanguine aspirant is undead." compset="CustomSpec" summary="Appearance betray you as an inhuman creature." uniqueness="unique">
    <usesource source="srcLibVamp"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpNN4"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNNWSAUsAu" name="Unsettling Aura" description="The sanguine aspirant&apos;s presence unsettles domesticated animals. All domesticated animals have a starting attitude of hostile towards the sanguine aspirant. The exact effects of this attitude adjustment will vary from animal to animal: dogs will likely bark at the sanguine aspirant, and may attack her, cats will similarly hiss and scratch, horses may rear or otherwise act nervously around her, and may even attack her, etc. Sanguine aspirant with this weakness suffer a -10 penalty on all Handle Animal and Ride checks involving domesticated animals, and, if the revenant has the wild empathy class feature, this penalty also applies to Diplomacy checks made with domesticated animals, as well. For the most part, non-domesticated animals are not affected by this ability, but at the GM&apos;s discretion, certain non- domesticated animals may act in the same way.\n\nCharacters that observe the way that animals react around the revenant may notice that something is amiss. Anyone that observes a domesticated animal responding to the sanguine aspirant in the above fashion that succeeds on a DC 20 Perception check notices that the animals are unusually unsettled by the sanguine aspirant, which may alert him to the revenant&apos;s true nature." compset="CustomSpec" summary="The sanguine aspirant&apos;s presence unsettles domesticated animals" uniqueness="unique">
    <usesource source="srcLibVamp"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpNN4"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    <eval phase="PreAttr" priority="10000"><![CDATA[      ~ If we're not enabled, get out now
      doneif (field[abilActive].value = 0)

      #skillbonus[skDiplo] -= 10
      #skillbonus[skHandleAn] -= 10
      #skillbonus[skRide] -= 10]]></eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNNWSAUnwl" name="Unwelcome" description="The sanguine aspirant has extreme difficulty entering a home or other private place without permission. Unless the sanguine aspirant is given an invitation to enter such a location by someone with the authority to do so, she must succeed on a Will save (DC 25) or be physically stopped at the entrance, unable to move forward or be moved forward by others. In the event of a failed save, the sanguine aspirant cannot try to enter that location again for 24 hours.\n\nIf the sanguine aspirant succeeds on the saving throw, she is able to enter the location, but suffers a -6 penalty on all of her ability scores for as long as she remains within the location, unless she receives an invitation from someone with the authority to do so while she is already inside.\n\n{b}Defining Private Places{/b}\n\nThe &quot;unwelcome&quot; weakness of the revenant template bars the revenant from entering homes and &quot;other private places,&quot; which begs the question of what, exactly, warrants a private place. While the final determination will always lie with the GM, we present the following guidelines to help determine what this ability does and does not apply to:\n\nWhile people may sleep there, the common room of an inn or similar establishment would not be considered &quot;private&quot; as it is available for public use.\n\nBy contrast, a specific rented room in an inn would likely count as such a place, as long as it was currently being rented by someone. Essentially, once the room has been rented, it is private for as long as it remains rented, as other guests are not allowed access.\n\nA private guild, gentleman&apos;s club, or other exclusive organization with a campus specifically for members only might count, depending on a few different factors. The more exclusive membership is (especially if it is based on criteria other than paying membership dues), the more likely it is to apply. Similarly, the more personal the nature of the club is, and the less that the activities that take place there have to do with work or business of any kind, the more likely it is to apply. The headquarters of a cult with elaborate initiation rituals would certainly apply, whereas the office of the local banker&apos;s guild would be less likely to.\n\nAbandoned homes, including ancient and forgotten temples and tombs, do not apply, even though they may technically be &quot;homes&quot; or &quot;private places.&quot;\n\nIn the case of buildings with a large number of residents, such as castles and keeps, especially those with multiple servants or an entire servants&apos; quarters, the building itself is not a &quot;private place&quot; for the purposes of this ability, but any individual personal quarters within the building would be." compset="CustomSpec" summary="Has extreme difficulty entering a home. Will save (DC 25)" uniqueness="unique">
    <usesource source="srcLibVamp"/>
    <tag group="SpecSource" tag="cHelpNN4"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super"/>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNNWLsWkns" name="Lose Weakness" description="At 6th level, and every six levels thereafter, a revenant occultist may choose a single lesser weakness that she gained as a result of gaining the revenant template, and lose it, forever freeing herself of that particular weakness. The revenant infiltrator may not choose to lose her blood dependency or sunlight vulnerability weaknesses in this way, nor can she lose any greater weaknesses as a result of this ability." compset="ClSpecial" summary="Remove a single lesser weakness">
    <usesource source="srcLibVamp"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Extra"/>
    <eval phase="Final" priority="10000"><![CDATA[~ If we're not shown, just get out now
doneif (tagis[Helper.ShowSpec] <> 1)
~ If we've been Disabled, get out now
doneif (tagis[Helper.SpcDisable] <> 0)

     hero.childfound[cfgNNWRvWk].field[cfgMax1].value -= 1]]></eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNNWChnEng" name="Channel Negative Energy" description="Beginning at 2nd level, a sweeblood manipulator can release a wave of negative energy in a manner similar to that used by clerics. This functions as the cleric class feature of the same name, except that the sweeblood manipulator does not need to use a holy symbol to channel positive energy, and the sweeblood manipulator can only channel negative energy in this way, regardless of alignment.\n\nAlternatively, if the sweeblood manipulator already possessed the ability to channel negative energy, his sweeblood manipulator levels stack with the levels of whichever class is granting him the ability to channel negative energy. If the sweeblood manipulator possessed the ability to channel positive energy, instead, then the two abilities do not stack, and the sweeblood manipulator channels positive energy and negative energy separately." compset="ClSpecial" summary="Can release a wave of negative energy">
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Super" name="Supernatural Ability" abbrev=" (Su)"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="ClExLose" name="ClExLose" abbrev="ClExLose"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="SpecUp"/>
    <tag group="Custom" tag="NN5ChanNeg" name="Sweeblood Channel Energy"/>
    <bootstrap thing="xChannel">
      <autotag group="Helper" tag="ChannelNeg"/>
      <autotag group="SpecialTab" tag="SQClsAbil"/>
      </bootstrap>
    <eval phase="PostLevel" priority="10500"><![CDATA[
      ~ If we're not shown, just get out now
      doneif (tagis[Helper.ShowSpec] = 0)
      
      ~ If we have an existing Channel Energy then add to it
      If (hero.tagis[Hero.ChanNeg] = 1) Then
        perform hero.findchild[Ability,"thingid.xChannel & Helper.ChannelNeg & Helper.ShowSpec & !SpecSource.cHelpNN5"].setfocus
        doneif (state.isfocus = 0)
        ~ Add our class level to the existing channel negetive energy ability found
        focus.field[abValue].value += field[xAllLev].value

      ~.. No existing Channel Negative Energy found setup our own
      Else
      
        ~perform hero.assign[Hero.ChanNeg]
        perform hero.assign[Custom.NN5ChanNeg]

        var tagexpr as string
        tagexpr = "SpecSource.cHelpNN5"
        call ChanEnFind
        doneif (state.isfocus = 0)

        ~ Add our class level to our turning level.
        focus.field[abValue].value += field[xAllLev].value
      Endif]]></eval>
    <eval phase="PostAttr" priority="10000" index="2"><![CDATA[
      ~ If we're not shown, just get out now
      doneif (tagis[Helper.ShowSpec] = 0)
      ~ If we don't have our own channel negative energy get out now!
      doneif (hero.tagis[Custom.NN5ChanNeg] <> 1)

      var tagexpr as string
      tagexpr = "SpecSource.cHelpNN5"
      call ChanEnFind
      doneif (state.isfocus = 0)

      ~ Set the number of uses
      focus.field[trkMax].value += 3 + #attrmod[aCHA]]]></eval>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNNWVmpP2" name="Vampiric Paramour 6th level" description="Beginning at 2nd level, a sweeblood manipulator attracts a vampiric paramour through the allure of her exotic and above-average blood, who serves her, either out of affection, friendship, or intense cravings for another taste of her blood. The vampiric paramour functions as a cohort, except that he must have the revenant template, and his maximum level is equal to the sweeblood manipulator&apos;s character level minus 5, rather than the sweeblood manipulator&apos;s character level minus 2 (the cohort&apos;s level is still also limited by the sweeblood manipulator&apos;s leadership score, as appropriate, and if the sweeblood manipulator already has Leadership, she suffers a -4 penalty to her leadership score for the purposes of both her vampiric paramour&apos;s maximum level and the maximum level of the cohort she gained from Leadership.  \n\nAt 6th level, the sweeblood manipulator can attract an additional vampiric paramour, though this one&apos;s maximum level is equal to the sweeblood manipulator&apos;s character level minus 6. Alternatively, she can increase the maximum level of her existing vampiric paramour by 2 (to be equal to her character level minus 3). \n\nAt 10th level, the sweeblood manipulator can attract a third vampiric paramour. This vampiric paramour&apos;s maximum level is equal to the sweeblood manipulator&apos;s character level minus 7. Alternatively, she can increase the maximum level of one of her existing vampiric paramours by 2." compset="ClSpecial" summary="Gain a Revenant Vampire Cohort">
    <fieldval field="actName" value="Gain a Revenant Vampire Cohort"/>
    <usesource source="srcLibVamp"/>
    <tag group="User" tag="Activation"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Extra"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="SpecUp"/>
    <bootstrap thing="minNNWVRe2">
      <containerreq phase="First" priority="2500"><![CDATA[count:Classes.NNWSweMan >= 6 & (fieldval:abilActive <> 0)]]></containerreq>
      </bootstrap>
    </thing>
  <thing id="cNNWVmpP3" name="Vampiric Paramour 10th level" description="Beginning at 2nd level, a sweeblood manipulator attracts a vampiric paramour through the allure of her exotic and above-average blood, who serves her, either out of affection, friendship, or intense cravings for another taste of her blood. The vampiric paramour functions as a cohort, except that he must have the revenant template, and his maximum level is equal to the sweeblood manipulator&apos;s character level minus 5, rather than the sweeblood manipulator&apos;s character level minus 2 (the cohort&apos;s level is still also limited by the sweeblood manipulator&apos;s leadership score, as appropriate, and if the sweeblood manipulator already has Leadership, she suffers a -4 penalty to her leadership score for the purposes of both her vampiric paramour&apos;s maximum level and the maximum level of the cohort she gained from Leadership.  \n\nAt 6th level, the sweeblood manipulator can attract an additional vampiric paramour, though this one&apos;s maximum level is equal to the sweeblood manipulator&apos;s character level minus 6. Alternatively, she can increase the maximum level of her existing vampiric paramour by 2 (to be equal to her character level minus 3). \n\nAt 10th level, the sweeblood manipulator can attract a third vampiric paramour. This vampiric paramour&apos;s maximum level is equal to the sweeblood manipulator&apos;s character level minus 7. Alternatively, she can increase the maximum level of one of her existing vampiric paramours by 2." compset="ClSpecial" summary="Gain a Revenant Vampire Cohort">
    <fieldval field="actName" value="Gain a Revenant Vampire Cohort"/>
    <usesource source="srcLibVamp"/>
    <tag group="User" tag="Activation"/>
    <tag group="AbilType" tag="Extra"/>
    <tag group="Helper" tag="SpecUp"/>
    <bootstrap thing="minNNWVRe3">
      <containerreq phase="First" priority="2500"><![CDATA[count:Classes.NNWSweMan >= 10 & (fieldval:abilActive <> 0)]]></containerreq>
      </bootstrap>
